# Literature Review: A Framework for Cyber-Risk Insurance against Ransomware: A Mixed-Method

Approach

## Introduction

Cybersecurity has become a critical concern for organizations across the globe. Hackers employ various
techniques, such as ransomware attacks, to exploit vulnerabilities in critical industries, resulting in
substantial financial losses, reputational damage, and customer churn. To address this growing threat,
researchers have proposed the development of a comprehensive cyber-risk insurance framework. This
literature review aims to synthesize and integrate research findings related to cyber-risk insurance against
ransomware, using a mixed-method approach.

## Ransomware Risk Management Model (R2M2)

One of the key research findings is the development of the Ransomware Risk Management Model (R2M2)
based on the protection motivation theory (PMT) [1]. The R2M2 provides a quantitative framework for
assessing and managing the risks associated with ransomware attacks. By integrating PMT principles,
the model considers both the threat appraisal and the protection motivation of organizations in mitigating
ransomware attacks.
The R2M2 comprises several modules, including the Ransomware Risk Assessment module. This module
allows organizations to evaluate the potential risks posed by ransomware attacks based on threat appraisal
[1]. By understanding the severity and likelihood of such attacks, organizations can make informed
decisions regarding risk mitigation strategies.

## Advanced Persistent Threat (APT)

Another significant research finding pertains to the role of advanced persistent threats (APTs) in ransomware attacks [4]. APTs refer to a class of sophisticated cyber threats that are targeted, stealthy, and
persistent. APTs often serve as the initial entry point for ransomware attacks, enabling hackers to infiltrate
critical industry firms and deploy ransomware payloads.
Understanding the nature and characteristics of APTs is crucial for developing effective cyber-risk insurance frameworks. By identifying and analyzing APTs, organizations can enhance their threat intelligence
